Ember here: So, probably ridiculous what I am doing here. Commenting on multiple of the songs I heard in the concert, but, ah, well. Someone might actually see. ;-) Anyway, so I really loved when that song was so early into the concert last week. I always liked the message of this song, but now that I actually heard the band live? Heard what the singer commented in-between? It means more. I am genuinely happy for them that they are the ones that are able to stand in front of the crowd and share their songs. I am sure it is hard. Tiring. Taxing. They do it anyway though and they appear to do it with heart. While I was certainly not clapping with a nosebleed, I honestly, genuinely wish all of them that they can not only perform but actually enjoy each of their songs. They sounded, from what little I heard, like they deserve it. Mind you, I am the kind of person, who wishes everyone the best, but they are people I can respect not only as muscians but as individuals. Ash, who was with me there at the concert and is completely blind, has a better ear for music. I on the other hand prefer to listen to the message behind the songs, the way they are sung, the way the instruments are played and the emotion behind it. What is said and how it is said. While even there she sometimes catches more than me, it is what truly sticks with me.  I am one person among many. One comment among thousands or even millions. Yet, I still want to tell imagine dragons as a whole and the singer in particular that I truly appreciate and heard the passion they put in the songs. And that what they said about depression truly resonated with me. My utmost respect for being so honest and saying it with so much conviction. Those were words many needed to hear. Thank you for saying them. They may have saved lives and certainly made me smile. You guys were wonderful live and should be proud of what you do! <3

In terms of music I hate this group tbh. Not gonna dwell on it for now, but this song has been there as background noise for so much of my life that it actually pisses me off. I mean it's kinda fitting that such an ass song would end up so consistently there for me, so now I actually appreciate it for that. A lot of people, in fact everyone I'd say sort of lives like they're the main character, but I'm especially guilty of this, and always have been. I live like I'm the main character of a tragic comedy or parody art film about our world (or my world I guess) and it's honestly pretty embarassing. The fact my world is so small and slow moving, or at least has been for most of my life, makes it impossible to shake this feeling. This song honestly makes me reflect on my entire life in such a beautiful way, I can't deny it's wormed it's way into having a special place in my heart.

"Thunder" by Imagine Dragons is a song about self-empowerment, individuality, and standing out from the crowd. The song's lyrics encourage listeners to celebrate their unique strengths and potential, and to resist societal pressures to conform.  The song's lyrics include, "Not a yes sir, not a follower. Fit the box, fit the mold. Have a seat in the foyer, take a number. I was lightning before the thunder".  "Thunder" was released in 2017 as the second single from Imagine Dragons' third studio album, Evolve. The song's music video was filmed in Dubai and features the band's lead singer, Dan Reynolds, singing and dancing among aliens.

The lyrics of "Thunder" by Imagine Dragons capture the journey of someone who feels different and refuses to conform to societal expectations. The narrator describes feeling like an outsider ("Not a 'Yes, sir,' not a follower") and dreaming of "bigger things," even when others mock or underestimate them. The "lightning before the thunder" imagery highlights the narrator's inner potential and ambition that might be unnoticed until it suddenly strikes with impact, like a storm. The recurring "thunder" represents the arrival of success or recognition after a period of being overlooked or dismissed. In the second verse, the narrator reflects on their school days, where they were laughed at while dreaming of making a difference for a larger audience. Now, they've reached a stage of success, with those who once doubted them cheering from afar ("in the nosebleeds"). The songâ€™s underlying message is about perseverance and self-belief, showing that even if people doubt or dismiss you, staying true to your dreams and pushing through can lead to eventual success.
